assets_used.asset_value: Sarah hates driving from Atlanta to Charlotte. She likes driving from Atlanta to Orlando.

correct_answer_label.label: You correctly chose the coordinating conjunctions that could be used to combine the two simple sentences into a compound sentence that makes sense.

hints.message: Coordinating conjunctions are used to combine simple sentences into one compound sentence.
A simple sentence has a subject and a verb and can stand on its own because it expresses a complete thought.

The coordinating conjunction shows the relationship between the two simple sentences. For example, the conjunction but can show that the two sentences have opposite ideas or that something unexpected happened. The conjunction and can show that the ideas in the sentences are similar to each other. The conjunction so can show a cause-and-effect relationship, or to how one idea follows logically from another.
Make sure the sentence makes sense when you add the conjunction. Try reading the sentence aloud—incorrect grammar usually sounds strange or unusual.
Remember to select ALL the conjunctions that could combine the two simple sentences into one compound sentence that makes sense.

item.instructional_prompt: Which conjunction could be used to combine the two simple sentences into one compound sentence? Select ALL that apply.
item.mechanical_prompt: Click or tap each correct answer.

misconception.label: So cannot be used to combine the two sentences. “She likes driving from Atlanta to Orlando” is not a result of the first sentence. So indicates a result. Try again.
Or does not make sense when combining the two sentences. Or is used to show a choice between two or more things. Try again.
Using nor would create a sentence that does not make sense: “Sarah hates driving from Atlanta to Charlotte, nor she likes driving from Atlanta to Orlando.” Try again.
You found one conjunction that can combine the two sentences, yet. Find another coordinating conjunction that has the same meaning as yet.
You found one conjunction that can combine the two sentences, but. Find another coordinating conjunction that has the same meaning as but.

wrong_answer_label.label: The correct choices are but and yet. Select these choices to move on to the next question.
